(44, 7, 14, 1, 45, 9, 11, 'called his father Jacob to him', 'Joseph''s Call to Jacob', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph''s invitation to Jacob and his family to come to Egypt. Acts 7:14 references the gathering of Jacob and his kindred, while Genesis 45:9-11 details Joseph''s command to bring them to him during the famine.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 14, 13, 2, 5, 6, 'all his kindred', 'Connection of Family Lineage', 'This connection highlights the theme of family lineage, as both passages reference the descendants of Jacob and his sons. Acts 7:14 mentions Jacob''s kindred, while 1 Chronicles 2:5-6 lists the sons of Judah, emphasizing the importance of genealogy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 14, 19, 105, 23, 23, 'his father Jacob to him', 'Joseph''s Family in Egypt', 'This connection highlights the arrival of Jacob and his family in Egypt, as mentioned in both passages. Acts 7:14 refers to Joseph calling his father Jacob and his kindred, while Psalms 105:23 notes Israel''s (Jacob''s) sojourn in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 15, 1, 49, 33, 33, 'he, and our fathers', 'Jacob''s Death and Burial', 'This connection highlights the moment of Jacob''s death in both passages. Acts 7:15 refers to Jacob''s death in Egypt, while Genesis 49:33 describes the circumstances of his passing and being gathered to his people.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 15, 2, 1, 6, 6, 'he, and our fathers,', 'Connection of Death in Egypt', 'Both passages emphasize the deaths of key figures in Egypt, linking Jacob''s descent with Joseph''s generation. This connection highlights the continuity of the Israelite narrative in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 15, 1, 46, 3, 7, 'Jacob went down into Egypt', 'Jacob''s Journey to Egypt', 'Both passages emphasize Jacob''s descent into Egypt, highlighting the significance of this event in the narrative of Israel''s formation. Acts 7:15 summarizes the outcome of this journey, while Genesis 46:3-7 details God''s promise and the circumstances surrounding it.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 15, 4, 20, 15, 15, NULL, 'Connection of Egypt and Fathers', 'Both passages emphasize the journey of Jacob and the fathers into Egypt, highlighting their shared experience. This connection illustrates the continuity of the Israelite narrative regarding their time in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 15, 5, 10, 22, 22, 'went down into Egypt', 'Connection of Egypt and Fathers', 'Both passages emphasize the journey of the fathers into Egypt, highlighting their initial descent and the subsequent growth of their descendants. This connection illustrates the significance of their migration as a foundational moment in Israel''s history.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 15, 5, 26, 5, 5, 'went down into Egypt', 'Connection of Egypt in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the journey of Jacob into Egypt, highlighting the significance of this migration in the formation of Israel as a nation. The mention of Egypt in both contexts underscores the transformative experience of the patriarchs and their descendants.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 15, 6, 24, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Jacob''s Journey', 'Both passages emphasize Jacob''s descent into Egypt, highlighting a significant moment in the patriarchal narrative. This connection illustrates the continuity of the family lineage as they transition to Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 16, 6, 24, 32, 32, 'Sychem', 'Burial in Shechem Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the burial of significant figures in Shechem, linking Abraham''s purchase and Joseph''s burial. This connection highlights the importance of Shechem as a burial site for the patriarchs.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 16, 1, 23, 16, 16, 'bought for a sum of money', 'Abraham''s Purchase of Burial Site', 'This connection highlights the act of Abraham purchasing a burial site, as both passages reference the transaction involving money for the sepulchre. Acts 7:16 mentions the sepulchre bought by Abraham, while Genesis 23:16 details the specific payment made for it.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 16, 2, 13, 19, 19, 'laid in the sepulchre', 'Connection of Burial and Bones', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of burial places for patriarchs. Acts 7:16 mentions the sepulchre of Abraham, while Exodus 13:19 focuses on the bones of Joseph, indicating a shared theme of honoring ancestral remains.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 16, 1, 33, 9, 20, 'the sepulchre that Abraham bought', 'Connection of Land and Purchase', 'Both passages emphasize the act of purchasing land in Shechem. Acts 7:16 refers to Abraham''s purchase, while Genesis 33:19 details Jacob''s acquisition of land from Hamor, linking their significance in the narrative of the patriarchs.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 16, 1, 34, 2, 31, 'Sychem', 'Connection between Shechem and Sychem', 'Both passages emphasize the location of Sychem, which is significant in the narrative of Dinah and Shechem''s actions. The mention of Sychem in Acts 7:16 connects to the events surrounding Dinah in Genesis 34, highlighting the importance of this city in Israel''s history.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 16, 1, 49, 29, 32, 'the sepulchre that Abraham bought', 'Burial Places of the Patriarchs', 'This connection highlights the significance of burial sites in the lineage of Abraham. Both passages reference the purchase of land for burial, emphasizing the importance of these locations in the patriarchal narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 17, 2, 1, 7, 12, 'the people grew and multiplied in Egypt', 'Growth of the Israelites', 'Both passages emphasize the multiplication of the Israelites in Egypt. Acts 7:17 refers to their growth as a fulfillment of God''s promise to Abraham, which is mirrored in Exodus 1:7-12, where the Israelites are described as increasing abundantly and becoming mighty.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 17, 1, 15, 13, 16, 'the time of the promise drew nigh', 'Promise of Affliction and Deliverance', 'This connection highlights the promise made to Abraham regarding his descendants'' future affliction in a foreign land, as seen in both passages. Acts 7:17 refers to the fulfillment of this promise as the people multiplied in Egypt, aligning with Genesis 15:13-16''s prophecy of their servitude and eventual deliverance.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 17, 19, 105, 24, 25, 'the people grew and multiplied in Egypt', 'Growth of God''s People', 'Both passages emphasize the growth of God''s people in Egypt. Acts 7:17 mentions their multiplication, while Psalms 105:24 highlights their increase and strength against enemies.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 17, 44, 7, 6, 6, 'the time of the promise drew nigh', 'Promise and Bondage Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the promise made to Abraham and the subsequent suffering of his descendants in Egypt. Acts 7:17 refers to the fulfillment of God''s promise, while Acts 7:6 speaks of the bondage that would precede it.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 17, 44, 13, 17, 17, 'the time of the promise', 'Promise and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s promise to Abraham and the subsequent deliverance of the Israelites from Egypt. Acts 7:17 mentions the time of the promise, while Acts 13:17 highlights God''s action in bringing the people out of Egypt.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 17, 2, 1, 20, 20, NULL, 'Multiplication of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the growth and multiplication of the people in Egypt. Acts 7:17 notes that the people grew and multiplied, while Exodus 1:20 states that the people multiplied and waxed very mighty.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 17, 61, 3, 8, 9, 'the promise drew nigh', 'God''s Promises and Timing', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s promises and their fulfillment over time. Both passages emphasize the certainty of God''s promises, with Acts referencing the promise to Abraham and 2 Peter affirming God''s faithfulness in His timing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 18, 2, 1, 8, 8, 'which knew not Joseph', 'Connection of New Kings', 'Both passages emphasize the emergence of a new king in Egypt who did not recognize Joseph. This highlights a significant shift in leadership and attitude towards the Israelites.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 19, 19, 105, 25, 25, 'dealt subtilly with our kindred', 'Connection of Subtle Dealing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of dealing subtly with God''s people. Acts 7:19 describes how the Egyptians treated the Israelites, while Psalms 105:25 notes how God turned hearts to hate His people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 19, 2, 1, 9, 22, 'evil entreated our fathers', 'Oppression of the Israelites', 'Both passages emphasize the evil treatment of the Israelites, leading to the casting out of their young children. Acts 7:19 reflects on the oppression described in Exodus 1:9-22, where Pharaoh''s decree results in the killing of male infants.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 19, 19, 83, 4, 5, 'evil entreated our fathers', 'Oppression of Israel', 'This connection highlights the theme of oppression faced by the Israelites. Both passages emphasize the intent to harm and eliminate the nation of Israel, reflecting a shared narrative of suffering and resistance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 19, 66, 12, 4, 5, 'cast out their young children', 'Connection of Child and Threat', 'Both passages emphasize the danger posed to children. In Acts, the young children are threatened by evil, while in Revelation, the dragon seeks to devour the child at birth.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 19, 19, 129, 1, 3, 'evil entreated our fathers', 'Affliction and Suffering Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of affliction faced by the people of Israel. Acts 7:19 describes the evil treatment of the fathers, while Psalms 129:1-3 reflects on the ongoing suffering and oppression experienced from youth.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
